Recursion versus iteration.

Recursion and iteration are equally powerful — anything you can do with recursion you can do with iteration, and vice versa. The choice is about clarity and practicality.

Use recursion when the problem is naturally recursive. Trees, graphs, divide-and-conquer, and structural problems on nested data all express cleanly as recursive functions. The code tends to match the mental model of the problem.

Use iteration when the recursion depth is unbounded or when performance is critical. Iterative code carries no per-call overhead from pushing and popping frames. And with an explicit stack — a plain list you manage yourself — you get the same logical structure as recursion without the depth limit.

The key mental model to carry forward is this: the call stack is literally a stack. Making it explicit by using a list does not change the algorithm — it just makes the stack visible and removes the system-imposed depth ceiling.
